    <id>https://doi.org/10.1257/aer.20241127</id>
    <title>Internal versus Institutional Barriers to Gender Equality: Evidence from British Politics</title>
    <updated>2026-05-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Noor Kumar, Uyseok Lee, Matt Lowe, Olaitan Ogunnote</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;American Economic Review&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Weekly lotteries determine which politicians ask the UK prime minister a question in front of a male-dominated, noisy chamber. Lottery winners receive 4 percent higher vote margin in the next election, but women are 12 percent less likely to submit questions than same-cohort men. The gender gap does not close with lottery-induced experience asking a question, but it closes after a format change, with questions asked to a smaller, quieter audience. The switch differentially draws in women with quieter voices. Our findings support institutional change, rather than experience, as a response to gender gaps in adversarial settings like the UK Parliament. (JEL D44, D72, J16)</content>
    <link href="https://doi.org/10.1257/aer.20241127"/>
    <category term="American Economic Review"/>
